    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-19T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-19T12:00:00-05:00" n="6"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d6">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Pacific War/1690: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Armour</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="18" xml:id="d6fn18">Repeated to the Ambassador in China in the
                        Department’s telegram No. 38, January 21, 11 p.m., for his information and
                        such comment as he might care to make.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-19T14:00:00-03:00"
                            >January 19, 1942—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 19—1:59 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>113. <hi rend="italic">La Prensa</hi> this morning published on first news page a
                    special United Press despatch dated Chungking, January 17, reporting an
                    interview by Frank Fisher<note n="19" xml:id="d6fn19">Francis M. Fisher, United
                        Press correspondent at Chungking.</note> with Dr. Sun Fo, President of the
                    [Legislative] Yuan, with following editorial note: <pb facs="0016" n="6"
                        xml:id="pg_6"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The following despatch which agrees with other reports on the Chinese
                            Nationalist Government’s great discontent over the manner in which the
                            Allies have conducted the war and intend to carry on the campaign is
                            highly significant.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>It seems to me that articles of this character written by American Press
                    correspondents are anything but helpful to the Allied cause.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Rio de Janeiro.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Armour</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
